04529nam a22007215i 9780801463648DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979590746  a97808014636487 a10.7591/97808014636482doi  a(DE-B1597)480046  a(OCoLC)754718627  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE185.2b.D38 2016 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a973.82231 aDavis, Hugh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut11a"We Will Be Satisfied With Nothing Less" :bThe African American Struggle for Equal Rights in the North during Reconstruction /cHugh Davis. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1. Launching the Equal Rights Movement -- t2. Toward the Fifteenth Amendment -- t3. The Crusade for Equal Access to Public Schools, 1864–1870 -- t4. The Equal Rights Struggle in the 1870s -- t5. The Republican Retreat from Reconstruction -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorians have focused almost entirely on the attempt by southern African Americans to attain equal rights during Reconstruction. However, the northern states also witnessed a significant period of struggle during these years. Northern blacks vigorously protested laws establishing inequality in education, public accommodations, and political life and challenged the Republican Party to live up to its stated ideals.In "We Will Be Satisfied With Nothing Less", Hugh Davis concentrates on the two issues that African Americans in the North considered most essential: black male suffrage rights and equal access to the public schools. Davis connects the local and the national; he joins the specifics of campaigns in places such as Cincinnati, Detroit, and San Francisco with the work of the National Equal Rights League and its successor, the National Executive Committee of Colored Persons. The narrative moves forward from their launching of the equal rights movement in 1864 to the "end" of Reconstruction in the North two decades later. The struggle to gain male suffrage rights was the centerpiece of the movement's agenda in the 1860s, while the school issue remained a major objective throughout the period. Following the ratification of the Fifteenth Amendment in 1870, northern blacks devoted considerable attention to assessing their place within the Republican Party and determining how they could most effectively employ the franchise to protect the rights of all citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy1863-1877. 0aEquality before the lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877). 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146364840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801463648.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK